[Atypical hemolytic uremic syndrome related to Oxalyplatin Cancer Chemotherapy 
responsive to Eculizumab].

[Article in Italian]

Zanchelli F, Tampieri E, Gozzetti F, Monti M, Martelli D, Graziani R, Zuffa E, 
Vincenzi D, Gamboni A, Buscaroli A.

We describe the case of a patient with adenocarcinoma of the colon treated with 
FOLFOX-4 (5-Fluorouracil, Folinic acid, Oxalyplatin), with subsequent appearance 
of atypical hemolytic uremic syndrome (aHUS). From 1999 to 2009, 13 cases of 
atypical HUS receiving chemotherapy with oxaliplatin have been described, as 
well as some sporadic cases. None of these cases has been treated with 
eculizumab. This is the first report of a patient with aHUS secondary to 
Oxalyplatin treated with Eculizumab. This treatment induced a complete remission 
of the syndrome and, later on, it has been discontinued with clinical and 
laboratory permanent remission. We identified some genetic mutations in this 
patient that might have a pathogenic role in the determining aHUS when 
associated with exposure to Oxalyplatin. Oxalyplatin withdrawal and its 
replacement to Irinotecan allowed the patient to receive first line chemotherapy 
continuation (FOLFIRI) with the same life expectancy and the same symptoms free 
period.

