We aimed to determine the distribution of ophthalmic care providers and its 
correlation with health and socioeconomic status and health system indicators. 
Data were gathered from the Iran Medical Council and the Iranian Societies of 
Ophthalmology and Optometry. Concurrent indicators were collected from the 
Statistical Center of Iran and national studies. A population-adjusted number of 
combined ophthalmologists and optometrists was used as the main dependent 
variable. Optometrist/ophthalmologist ratio was 0.9. We had 1 ophthalmologist 
and 1 optometrist for every 40 000 and 45 000 individuals, respectively. We 
observed a direct correlation between the number of ophthalmologists, 
optometrists and life expectancy at the provincial level. Gross provincial 
income and expenditure and provincial literacy were correlated as well. 
Provincial unemployment had a negative correlation. Provincial hospital 
statistics and population density were also significantly correlated. The 
Islamic Republic of Iran has met the World Health Organization's desired per 
capita number of ophthalmologists and optometrists, but there is wide variation 
in their density.

